<section>
<title>The Mïmis Filesystem</title>

<p>It currently takes some technological savvy to comprehend the state of the Mïmis network. If you have some of that, you might like to check out:</p>

<ul>
  <li><a href="http://repo.dhappy.org/.../git/">Git Repository</a> (<a href="https://github.com/wholcomb/tip"><acronym title="Graphical User Interface">GUI</acronym></a>) (<a href=".../">Instantiated</a>)</li>
  <li><a href="crx">Chrome Extension</a></li>
  <li><a href="http://groups.google.com/group/tip-dev">Developers Listserv</a></li>
</ul>

<section>
<title>1.0 – Mïmis</title>

<section>
<title>Structure</title>

<ol>
<li>User</li>
<li><a href="http://www.google.com/chrome/">Chrome</a></li>
<li><a href="Chrome/extension/">Chrome extension</a></li>
<li><a href="java/src/">Java</a> <a href="java/src/org/dhappy/mimis/CacheAgentApplet.java">applet</a></li>
<li><a href="http://neo4j.org">Neo4j</a></li>
</ol>

<p>Neo4j holds <a href=".../blog/Compression Trees/">hash trees</a> and semantic overlays over them. In essence, a user just keeps coming up with terms related to what they're searching for and the available graph is partitioned based on those descriptors.</p>

<p>The hash trees allow cache agents on disperate machines to communicate very succinctly about the state of the hash. They are communicating graph shards. Which is sorta what is happening currently with xml, there's just no widespread support for things like <a href="http://www.w3.org/TR/xinclude/">xinclude</a>.</p>
</section>

<section>
<title>Cache Agents</title>

<p>The cache metadata are maintained through a variety of agents:</p>

<ul>
<li><a href="java/src/org/dhappy/mimis/FileLoader.java">File System</a></li>
<li><a href="java/src/org/dhappy/mimis/SmackGMailConnection.java"><acronym title="Extensible Message Passing Protocol">XMPP</acronym></a></li>
<li><a href="http://mina.apache.org/">P2P</a></li>
<li>HTTP</li>
</ul>
</section>

<section>
<title>Importance</title>
<p>Understanding the importance of Mïmis is easiest in terms of using the filesystem. I'll try to <a href=".../blog/Compression Trees/">approach it incrimentally</a>.</p>
</section>

